Section 1: Outliers in Different Distributions

1.1: Normal Distribution

  1. Setting up R and N
r <- 1000
n <- 1000
  1. R means of N standard norms
x <- sapply(1:n, function(s) mean(rnorm(n)))
  1. Mean of means:
mean(mean(x))
## [1] -0.001358412

Standard Deviation:

sd(x)
## [1] 0.03139243

Confidence Interval:

left <- quantile(x, 0.025)
left
##        2.5% 
## -0.05744188
right <- quantile(x, 0.975)
right
##      97.5% 
## 0.06235388

  1. Based on the theoretical considerations, with an increase in sample sizes we can expect the confidence interval to decrease since it decreases the standard error. The larger the sample size, the less uncertainty there is about the true population mean, and the estimate becomes more precise. In this particular scenario, I am 95% confident that the true mean of this dataset lies between 6.190 and 24594.86 with a sample size of 1,000.

  2. Different Sample Sizes

r2 <- 1000
n2 <- 10
x2 <- sapply(1:n2, function(s) mean(rnorm(n2)))
mean(mean(x2))
## [1] -0.06925348
sd(x2)
## [1] 0.2151612
left <- quantile(x2, 0.025)
left
##      2.5% 
## -0.401724
right <- quantile(x2, 0.975)
right
##     97.5% 
## 0.2266566

With a sample size decreased to 10, we see that the confidence interval (still at 95%) has a wider range, with values from -0.304 to 0.496.

1.2: Pareto Distribution

  1. K Values in Pareto

  2. There is more of a distribution shown when k = 10 and 100 versus when k = 1. The distribution is more spread for when k = 100 than the other k values, however both k = 10 and 100 histograms show a large right skew and a heavy tail. The shapes of these histograms do not follow a normal distribution. A high proportion of the graph has low values, whereas a low proportion of the graph has high values.

  3. Different K and N values

k_less <- 0.5
k_greater <- 2
r <- 1000
n1 <- 10
n2 <- 1000
n3 <- 10000

# Sample size is 10, and k is 0.5.
x_pareto_less <- sapply(1:n1, function(s) mean(rpareto(n1, 1, k_less)))

## 5.634691

sd(x_pareto_greater)

##     2.5%

left_greater_2 <- quantile(x_pareto_greater_2, 0.025)
right_greater_2 <- quantile(x_pareto_greater_2, 0.975)
left_greater_2
##     2.5% 
## 1.847513
right_greater_2
##    97.5% 
## 2.261022
  1. From changing the sample sizes and lower bounds in the Pareto distribution, my findings show that the standard deviations and confidence regions (95%) vary widely. In the case of a normal distribution, the sample size affects the confidence interval; the smaller the sample size, the wider the confidence interval gets. With the Pareto distribution, the sample size does not seem to affect it as much as the k-value. When sampling with n = 10 and 1000, the standard deviations and confidence regions stayed relatively the same. However, when k was increased to 2, the standard deviation was much smaller and the confidence interval was narrow. (I was unable to try for k = 10000 due to runtime errors.)

Section 2: Linear Transformation of Images

2.1: Rotate Matrices

  1. Rotate Matrix A
A <- matrix(c(0,0, 0,2, 1,1), 3, 2, byrow = TRUE)
plot(A[,1], A[,2], type ="l", asp=1)

Rot <- function(alpha) {
  a <- alpha*pi/180
  matrix(c(cos(a), sin(a), -sin(a), cos(a)), 2, 2)
}

A_1 <- A%*%Rot(45)
plot(A_1[,1], A_1[,2], type ="l", asp=1)

A_2 <- A%*%Rot(-225)
plot(A_2[,1], A_2[,2], type ="l", asp=1)

A_3 <- A%*%Rot(60)
plot(A_3[,1], A_3[,2], type ="l", asp=1)

  1. Create new matrix object “B”
B <- matrix(c(2,3, 5,6, 10,-12), 3, 2, byrow = TRUE)
B
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    2    3
## [2,]    5    6
## [3,]   10  -12
  1. Rotate Matrix B
plot(B[,1], B[,2], type="b", asp=1 )

B_1 <- B%*%Rot(60)
plot(B_1[,1], B_1[,2], type="b", asp=1)

B_2 <- B%*%Rot(120)
plot(B_2[,1], B_2[,2], type="b", asp=1)

B_3 <- B%*%Rot(-180)
plot(B_3[,1], B_3[,2], type="b", asp=1)

Rot <- function(alpha) {
  a <- alpha*pi/180

}
transMatrix1 <- mat[,1:2]%*%Rot(60)
transMatrix1.df <- cbind(transMatrix1[,1:2], mat[,3])

2.3: Flip and Stretch

  1. Flip matrix over y-axis
X <- matrix(c(1,0, 1,3, 2,3), 3, 2, byrow = TRUE)
plot(x = X[,1], y =X[,2], type="l", asp=1)

X_flip<- X%*%matrix(c(-1, 0, 0, 1), 2, 2)
plot(X_flip[,1], X_flip[,2], type="l", asp=1)

  1. Stretch matrix object
X_stretch <- X%*%matrix(c(1, 0, 0, 2), 2, 2) 
plot(X_stretch[,1], X_stretch[,2], type="l", asp=1)

  1. Transform Crazy Hat object
flipStretchMatrix <- function(mat, alpha, stretchFactor){
  mat <- mat[,1:2] %*% Rot(alpha)
  mat[,2] <- mat[,2] * stretchFactor
  return(mat)
}
flipStretchData <- function(data, alpha, stretchFactor){
  matrix_flip <- data.matrix(data)
  matrix_flip <- flipStretchMatrix(matrix_flip, alpha, stretchFactor)
  data$x <- matrix_flip[,1]
  data$y <- matrix_flip[,2]
  ggplot(data, aes(x, y, group=group)) + geom_path()
}
flipStretchData(data, 45, 3)

  1. To modify the matrix in which post-multiply and pre-multiply outputs the same result, a conversion using the transpose function would yield the same result. The equivalent to (AB) would be to multiply the transposed B by transposed A and transpose the entire result. The equation would look like: A x B = (B’ x A’)’.
